Introduction

Here is a brief introduction to the LearnBayes package.

library(LearnBayes)

Specifying a Bayesian Model

We start with a Bayesian model. Using the familiar cars dataset, we fit a simple regresssion model.

\[ y_i \sim N(a + b \, \, x_i), i = 1, ..., n \]

\[ a \sim N(0, 100), b \sim N(0, 10), \sigma \sim unif(0, 50) \] We define the log posterior of Bayesian model by the alist function as a function.

my_log_posterior <- function(theta, y, x){
  a <- theta[1]
  b <- theta[2]
  sigma <- exp(theta[3])
  log_likelihood <- sum(dnorm(y, a + b * x, sigma, 
                              log=TRUE))
  log_prior <- dnorm(a, 0, 100, log=TRUE) +
              dnorm(b, 0, 10, log=TRUE) +
              dunif(sigma, 0, 50, log=TRUE) +
              log(sigma)
  log_likelihood + log_prior
}

Approximate Normal Fit to Posterior

To obtain an approximate normal fit to the posterior, use the laplace function.

fit1 <- laplace(my_log_posterior, c(-17, 3, 2), 
                cars$dist, cars$speed)

The mode and var components give the mean vector and the var-cov matrix of the approximation.

fit1$mode
## [1] -17.405143   3.921162   2.722889
fit1$var
##              [,1]          [,2]          [,3]
## [1,] 44.493074963 -2.5894897628  0.0035294481
## [2,] -2.589489763  0.1682266015 -0.0002282984
## [3,]  0.003529448 -0.0002282984  0.0102074367

Metropolis Random Walk Sampler

The rwmetrop function takes a simulated sample from the posterior using the random walk algorithm.

fit2 <- rwmetrop(my_log_posterior,
          proposal = list(var=fit1$var, scale=1.5),
          start = fit1$mode,
          m = 10000,
          cars$dist, cars$speed)

Some MCMC Diagnostics

Look at acceptance rate of sampler.

fit2$accept
## [1] 0.2948

Construct trace and density plots of simulated draws for each parameter.

library(coda)
plot(mcmc(fit2$par))

Density plot of sigma (exponentiating simulated draws of log sigma):

library(ggplot2)
simulated_draws <- data.frame(fit2$par)
names(simulated_draws) <- c("a", "b", "log_sigma")
ggplot(simulated_draws, aes(exp(log_sigma))) +
  geom_density()
